# Changelog

## `dylib` class is now `dylib::library`

`dylib` is now a namespace, the main class is now `dylib::library`.

## Library name decorator changes

Now, by default, no decorators are applied to the library name, you should use for example `dylib::decorations::os_default()`

`dylib` 2.0
```c++
// Windows -> "./plugins/foo.dll"
// MacOS   -> "./plugins/libfoo.dylib"
// Linux   -> "./plugins/libfoo.so"
dylib lib("./plugins/foo");
```

`dylib` 3.0
```c++
// Windows -> "./plugins/foo.dll"
// MacOS   -> "./plugins/libfoo.dylib"
// Linux   -> "./plugins/libfoo.so"
dylib::library lib("./plugins/foo", dylib::decorations::os_default());
```

Custom decorations can now be applied to the library name.
New macros `DYLIB_WIN_OTHER` and `DYLIB_WIN_MAC_OTHER` can be useful for this case.

```c++
// Windows -> "./plugins/foo.dll"
// MacOS   -> "./plugins/libfoo.so"
// Linux   -> "./plugins/libfoo.so"
auto custom_decorations = dylib::decorations(
    DYLIB_WIN_OTHER("", "lib"), // prefix
    DYLIB_WIN_OTHER(".dll", ".so"), // suffix
);
dylib::library lib("./plugins/foo", custom_decorations);
```

## Support of cross-platform and cross-compiler C++ mangled symbols gathering

Now, `dylib::library` supports mangled C++ symbols loading.
Function or variable signature must be provided as template parameter of get_function or get_variable.
Their namespace path (if present) and their arguments must be provided as string representation.

The format for the function arguments is the following:
type [const] [volatile] [*|&|&&]

```c++
dylib::library lib("./plugins/foo", dylib::decorations::os_default());

auto plugin_init = lib.get_function<int(int, char const * const *)>("plugin::core::init(int, char const * const *)");
auto plugin_name = lib.get_variable<std::string>("plugin::info::name");

int result = plugin_init(ac, av);
std::cout << "plugin " << plugin_name << " initialized with return code " << result << std::endl;
```

## Support of cross-platform symbols listing

Now, the collection of the list of symbols contained in a dynamic library is available:

```c++
dylib::library lib("./plugins/foo", dylib::decorations::os_default());

auto symbols = lib.symbols();

for (auto &sym : symbols)
    if (sym.loadable) std::cout << s.demangled_name << std::endl;
```

# Drop of support

System libraries cannot be gathered anymore without specifying a full path:

`dylib` 2.0
```c++
dylib lib("kernel32");
auto GetCurrentThreadId = lib.get_function<DWORD()>("GetCurrentThreadId");
```

`dylib` 3.0
```c++
dylib::library lib("\Windows\system32\Kernel32.dll");
auto GetCurrentThreadId = lib.get_function<DWORD()>("GetCurrentThreadId");
```

# Changelog

## Dylib class is now RAII compliant

`open()`, `close()` and `default constructor` are not available anymore

## Dylib constructor changes

```c++
// old API
dylib lib("./libs/libfoo", dylib::extension);

// new API
dylib lib("./libs", "foo");
```
The dylib class can now load a dynamic library from the system library path
```c++
// Load "foo" library from the system library path

dylib lib("foo");
```
The dylib class will now automatically add os decorations (os prefix and suffix) to the library name, but you can disable that by setting decorations parameter to false
```c++
// Windows -> "foo.dll"
// MacOS   -> "libfoo.dylib"
// Linux   -> "libfoo.so"

dylib lib("foo");

// Windows -> "foo.lib"
// MacOS   -> "foo.lib"
// Linux   -> "foo.lib"

dylib lib("foo.lib", false);
```

## Changes on get_function return type

The return type of `get_function` is now a function pointer instead of an `std::function`
```c++
// old API
std::function<double(double, double)> adder = lib.get_function<double(double, double)>("adder");

// new API
double (*adder)(double, double) = lib.get_function<double(double, double)>("adder");
```

## Changes on handle_error exception

`handle_error` exception is now called `load_error`

```c++
try {
    dylib lib("foo");
    lib.get_function<double(double, double)>("adder");
}

// old API
catch (const dylib::handle_error &e) {
    std::cout << e.what() << std::endl;
}

// new API
catch (const dylib::load_error &e) {
    std::cout << e.what() << std::endl;
}
```

## DYLIB_API is not available anymore

To ensure the functions and variable of your future dynamic library will be exported on windows, you can use the following macro
```c++
#if defined(_WIN32) || defined(_WIN64)
#define LIB_EXPORT __declspec(dllexport)
#else
#define LIB_EXPORT
#endif
```
Or, you can add the following cmake rule that will export all symbols on windows
```cmake
if(MSVC)
    set(CMAKE_WINDOWS_EXPORT_ALL_SYMBOLS TRUE)
endif()
```
> Make sure to mark the functions and variables you want to export as `extern "C"` to avoid name mangling

## The cmake rule that disable lib prefixes is now useless

Since `dylib` now handles libs prefix, you will need to remove the following cmake rule when building your dynamic libs
```cmake
# remove the following rule from your cmakelists if you was using it with dylib 1.X.X
set_target_properties(target PROPERTIES PREFIX "")
```

# Thanks

Huge thanks to @eyalroz for his help and contributions that made this update possible !

# Changelog

- feat: `has_symbol` function
- feat: `operator bool()`
- feat: Valgrind CI

# Examples

## has_symbol
```c++
void dylib_symbol_example(const dylib &lib)
{
    if (lib.has_symbol("GetModule"))
        std::cout << "GetModule has been found" << std::endl;
    else
        std::cout << "Could not found GetModule symbol" << std::endl;
}
```

## operator bool()
```c++
void dylib_status_example(const dylib &lib)
{
    if (lib)
        std::cout << "something is curently loaded in the dylib object" << std::endl;
    if (!lib)
        std::cout << "nothing is curently loaded in the dylib object" << std::endl;
}
```
